topic.title: Introduction

li.p: Ingress data processing subsystem is a functional unit that processes an input data stream read from the controller memory and then writes the processed output data stream back to controller memory as shown in the following figure:

fig.title: Ingress Data Processing Unit Top Level Block

li.p: Ingress data processing subsystem includes data protection information processing engine 1 (PI1) and engine 2 (PI2), and an encryption engine.
The input data stream to ingress processing subsystem is defined by the source SGL and the output data stream is defined by the destination SGL in a request message.
The sequence of data processing is fixed: Input data stream ⇨ PI1 ⇨ PI2 ⇨ Encryption ⇨ Output data stream.
Each data processing engine can be enabled or disabled individually, except in the case where PI1 is disabled, P2 has to be disabled.
Output data stream from each engine will be streamlined directly, instead of being stored and then forwarded, to next engine or controller memory.

Ingress data processing subsystem processes inbound ingress DPS request messages received on one Ingress DPS inbound message queue, then initiates a data transfer and data processing from controller memory. After data processing and transfer completion, it sends out outbound ingress DPS completion messages, if needed, either on one Ingress DPS outbound message queue (for non-cascaded cases) or stored in a specified memory location (for cascaded cases).
Ingress data processing subsystem supports both inbound concise message and inbound extended message format.
Ingress data processing subsystem supports both outbound concise message and outbound extended message format.

ul.li: A total of 32 inbound message queues and 16 outbound message queues are supported.

topic.title: Generic Data Stream Processing

li.p: All ingress DPS engines operate on a data stream per inbound message request.

The input data stream to ingress DPS is read from a logical buffer defined by the source SGL. The input data stream length is equal to the size of the logical buffer, which is the sum of all memory region sizes specified in all source SGL elements as shown in the following figure:

fig.title: Ingress DPS Input Data Stream and Source SGL

li.p: The output data stream from ingress DPS is written to a logical buffer defined by the destination SGL. The output data stream length can be larger or smaller than input data stream length depending on each functional engine operation configurations. The output data stream length must be equal to or less than logical buffer size, which is the sum all memory region sizes specified in all destination SGL elements. If the output data stream length is larger than the logical buffer size, a destination SGL overflow error will be declared in outbound message (MsgStatus = DstSGLOvf) and the overflow data will be discarded, both cases are shown in the following two figures:

fig.title: Ingress DPS Output Data Stream and Destination SGL - Normal
Ingress DPS Output Data Stream and Destination SGL - Destination SGL Overflow

li.p:
The input data steam to each functional engine is either from the output data stream of the upstream functional engine or from the ingress DPS input data stream if the functional engine is configured as the first operation engine. The output data stream from each function engine is either sent to the downstream functional engine or is sent out as ingress DPS output data stream if the functional engine is configured as the last operation engine. All functional engines operate in a block-based operation.
The following two data fields are in the inbound message: Input block size (BlkSize) and data offset (DataOffset). The data offset is where the first block starts. Data between the start of the input data stream and the data offset is directly passed through from input to output, as shown in Figure 4. If the end of the input data stream is not aligned to the input block boundary, a partial block is generated. The partial block detection is not an error situation in the ingress DPS, but is reported in the outbound message, and the partial block is passed directly to the output data stream, as shown in Figure 5
The ingress DPS processes the input data stream from the first block to the last block, but not partial blocks at beginning or at the end.
The output block size is inferred as result of data processing in a functional engine. Block-Based Operation
Block Based Operation with Partial Block Detected

topic.title: Data Protect Information Processing

li.p:
The ingress data processing subsystem contains two cascaded protection information (PI) processing engines PI1 and PI2. Each engine performs an identical function but is configured independently in the inbound message request.
The protection information field, is always located in the last 8 bytes of a block.
Both PI1 and PI2 engines support the three types of protection information formats. The format for each protection information is shown as in the following figure: Formats for Protection Information
NVMe data protection information provides T10 DIF- or DIX-like protection.
The guard field contains a CRC16 computed over the contents of the corresponding block data. The CRC16 uses the generator polynomial G(x) = 0x18BB7. See ISO/IEC 14776-323, and SCSI Block Commands (SBC-3) [T10/1799-D] for details regarding CRC16 computation.
The application tag contains application specific data.
The reference tag identifies the address of the sector and is used to ensure that the correct sector is transferred.
Extended Protection Information
The guard field contains a CRC32 computed over the contents of the corresponding block data. The CRC32 uses CRC-32C (Castagnoli) with generator polynomial G(x) = 0x1EDC6F41.
The reference tag identifies the address of the block and is used to ensure that the correct block is transferred.
CRC64 Protection Information
The guard field contains a CRC64 computed over the contents of the corresponding sector data. The CRC64 uses CRC64-ECMA-182 with generator polynomial G(x) = 0x42F0E1EBA9EA3693.
Protection information type is configured per inbound message request in the field of PI1PIMode and P2PIMode for PI1 and PI2 engines, respectively.
The protection information processing supports three operation modes: check and forward, check and strip, and insert as shown in the following figure. The operation mode is set per inbound message request. PI Operation Modes
When the operation mode is set to check and forward mode, the PI gets checked and then forwarded to output data stream. The PI operation mode is set to this mode by setting inbound message field PI1OpMode or PI2OpMode to ChkFwd. There is no block size change as a result of check and forward operation. The protection information can be enabled or disabled individually for each field by the inbound message field PI1GardEn, P1AppTagEn, and P1RefTagEn for PI1 engine, or PI2GardEn, P2AppTagEn, and P2RefTagEn for PI2 engine, respectively. If enabled, the corresponding PI field in the input data block is checked against locally computed value, if there is a mismatch, a PI error is detected.
When the operation mode is set to check and strip mode, the PI gets checked and then stripped out from the input block. The PI operation mode is set to this mode by setting the inbound message field PI1OpMode or PI2OpMode to ChkStrip. The output block size is reduced by 8 Bytes as a result of check and strip.
When the operation mode is set to insert mode, the locally computed PI field is inserted at end of each block. The PI operation mode is set to this mode by setting inbound message field PI1OpMode or PI2OpMode to Insert. The output block size is increased by 8 Bytes as a result of check and insert.
The PI field values used for PI check and insertion operation are computed using the input data block and the parameters from the inbound message.
CRC value is computed over the user data per input block. The initial CRC seed for CRC generation can be selected either from register PI1DefaultSeed and PI2DefaultSeed or from message field PI1CRCSeed and PI2CRCSeed. The CRC seed is selected by PI1CRCSeedSel or PI2CRCSeedSel in the message. The CRC seed is either constant across all input blocks for the current request, or incremental per input block set by PI1SeedMode and PI2SeedMode in the request message. The CRC generated is optionally inverted before being used for check or insertion by setting message field PI1CRCInv to 1.
The application tag is always constant across all input blocks for the current request, and is set to message field P1PIAppTag or P2PIAppTag. The PI operation mode is set to check and forward or check and strip, the application tag check is masked bit wise by PI1AppTagMask or PI2AppTagMask bit vectors provided by inbound message request.
The reference tag is either constant across all input blocks for the current request, or incremented per input block. The value in constant mode or in incremental mode, which is the reference tag value for the first block for the current request, is set to inbound message field PI1RefTagInit or PI2RefTagInit.
PI checking may be disabled as a side effect of the content of the protection information field in a block from input data stream. The PI Check Disable Mode (P1ChkDisableMode or PI2ChkDiableMode) field in the message request controls the disabling of the protection information.
When the PI1ChkDisableMode or PI2ChkDisableMode field is set to Never, then enabled protection information checking is never disabled as a side effect of the contents of the protection information fields.
When the PI1ChkDisableMode or PI2ChkDisableMode field is set to AppTag, then enabled protection formation checking is disabled for that sector only if the protection information application tag field has a value of 0xFFFF.
When the PI1ChkDisableMode or PI2ChkDisableMode field is set to AppRefTag, then enabled protection formation checking is disabled for that sector only if the protection information application tag field has a value of 0xFFFF and the protection information reference tag field has a value of 0xFFFF_FFFF.
The PI1ChkDisableMode or PI2ChkDisableMode field has no effect on insert operation when the inbound message request is set to insert.

The cascaded PI engines PI1 and PI2 are intended to do the following two types of system level PI processing:
PI replacement processing, where the PI field from the incoming data block is checked and striped, and a new PI field is inserted with the same or different block size.
Nested PI processing, where two PI fields with different block sizes are in the data stream as shown in the following figure.
Nested PI Layers
In both the above cases, PI2 engine cannot be configured independently, and the following rules apply.
PI2 is enabled only if PI1 is enabled.
The output data block of PI1 is always aligned to input block of PI2 at start of the blocks.

PI operation may trigger a separate early PI completion in addition to ingress DPS completion. The early PI completion is triggered by PI1 or PI2 after PI operation completes, while normal ingress DPS completion is triggered after all operations gets completed. Early PI completion is only triggered for data flows where PI1 or PI2 are not the last operation. The early PI completion is enabled per inbound message request by PICplMsgEn. The early PI completion has the format as the normal ingress DPS completion with CplTyp set to 1 (PI).

topic.title: Hash Engine

li.p: Hash engine in ingress data processing unit performs hashing operation as a side effect of the fly by data. The output data stream of the hash engine is identical to the input data stream, the hashed digest(s) is captured in completion message.

The secure hashing algorithm implemented in hash engine is compliant to FIPS 202 Standard "SHA-3 Standard: Permutation-Based Hash and Extendable-Output Functions", August 2015. Two hash functions SHA3-256 and SHA3-512 are supported in the hash engine. The function SHA3-256 or SHA3-512 is selected by HashAglSel in the ingress DPU request message.
The high performance hash engine supports up to 10 GB/s throughput for function SHA3-256 and 5 GB/s for function SHA3-512.

For data integrity check, two hash engines are implemented, the digests from the two engines are compared, if they are not matching, the data integrity check status will be set in the completion message as shown in the following figure:

Hash engine hashes input data stream starting from the offset location specified by the HashDataOffset field in the request message. Hash engine supports two operation modes: block based hash operation and stream based hash operation. Hash operation mode is selected by HashOpMode field in the request message.

For block based operation (HashOpMode = 0 (Block)), see Figure 2. The input data stream consists of one or multiple data blocks, and depending on the HashDataOffset value and input data stream length; it may also have offset data portion at the beginning and partial data block at the end. Both offset data at the beginning of the input data stream and partial data block at the end of the input data stream are skipped from hash operation. Hash operation starts with the default initial context in the hash engine for each data block and generates one digest for each data block. The data block size is fixed for all data blocks in the input data stream for the current request and is specified by HashBlkSize field in the request message. Optionally, hash engine may skip up to some dwords at the end of every data block from hashing operation depending on the HashSkipNum value.

Block based operation supports SHA3-256 and SHA3-512 functions, and total data block number supported is 8 (N<=7) for SHA3-256 function and 4 (N<=3) for SHA3-512 function. If the data block number is larger than the specified number then request message format error will be declared in completion message.

For stream based hashing operation, see Figure 3. Multiple stream based hashing operations can be cascaded such that one digest is generated by cascading multiple input data streams from multiple requests. There are four operation modes for stream based hash operations specified in HashOpMode field in the request message. The first operation in cascaded operations (HashOpMode=1 (StartCont)) that starts with default context in hash engine and keep the intermediate hash context in the hash engine after the operation. The operations (HashOpMode=StreamContCont)) between the first and the last operations start with the intermediate context in hash engine left from the previous operation, and keep the intermediate hash context after the current operation. The last operation (HashOpMode=3) starts with the intermediate context left from the previous operation and generates the final hash digest. For single stream based operation (HashOpMode=4(StreamStartEnd)), it starts with default context in hash engine and generates the hash digest after the operation.
The stream based operation supports both SHA3-256 and SHA3-512 functions. There are two limitations for cascaded operations:
Cascaded stream based operations can not be interleaved with other hash operations since context switch is not supported in the hash engine.

If it is not the last operation (HashOpMode =1 or 2), the input data stream size has to be multiple of 132 bytes for function SHA3-256 or 72 bytes for function SHA3-512. This is because hash engine does not support input data residuals for cascaded operations.

Hash engine is used for HMAC-SHA3-256 and HMAC-SHA3-512 digest generation with multiple steps. The algorithm is complaint to FIPS 198-1 2008 but with SHA3-256/512 function for hashing steps. An HMAC operation uses the following formula:
HMAC(K, text) = H((K0 XOR opad) || H((K0 XOR ipad) || text))

strow.stentry: The input message to be hashed
The preprocessed MAC Key: Padded with zero from K is the length of K is less than the block size, or hashed key if the length of K is more than the block size.
The block size in bytes of the used algorithm: 136-byte for SHA3-256, 72-byte for SHA3-512
Inner hash pad value: 0x36 repeated B (block size) times
Outer hash pad value: 0x5c repeated B (block size) times

li.p: The HMAC operation consists of three steps. The first part is the MAC Key processing. The second part is the inner hash operation and as final step the outer hash operation is performed. Firmware is responsible to perform all the three steps and generates the hash request messages for hash operations by hash engine in the last two steps.

If hash engine is the only enabled data processing engine in the ingress DPU, and no output data stream is needed, a dummy destination SGL is defined in the request message with DestMemDumpX set to 1 in every SGL element in the dummy destination SGL.

The hash digests generated by hash engine are part of completion message. Depending the digest number, which is less or equal to 8, and compression meta data number, which is less than or equal to 9 whenever hash operation is enabled, the completion message format and length varies. When there is only one SHA3-256 digest generated, Digest 0 can be located at offset of 8 dwords or 16 dwords in the completion message, selected by HASHDigest0Offset in the request message. With 8 dwords offset option, the digest 0 is in the 64-byte cache line of the completion message, that optimizes the completion message transfer and processing. For various digest numbers, the completion message formats are shown in Figure 4 for SHA3-256 and Figure 5 for SHA3-512.

topic.title: Compression Engine

li.p: Compression engine in ingress data processing unit performs data compression operation on the input data stream from upstream data processing engine (PI1, PI2 or Hash) in the ingress data processing unit, and the output data stream generated from the compression engine is the compressed data stream and it is sent to downstream data processing engine (encryption engine) in the ingress processing unit or directly sent out to BRAM or SDRAM. Figure 1 shows the top level block diagram. The data structures are denoted with data structure numbers which are defined in Figure 3

Compression engine consists 8 slices. Each slice consists one compression core, decompression core and one packing function. The compression core supports zlib compression with static Huffman encoding scheme and a history buffer of 2048B. The decompression core is used for data integrity check which decompresses compressed data and then compares the decompressed data with input uncompressed data. Packing function packs compressed data, meta data, CRC into compressed data blocks.

The compression engine supports block based compression operation only. For block based compression, the compression engine compresses every input uncompressed data block atomically starting with default history buffer, the output compressed data for each input uncompressed data block, together together with compression meta data and CRC, is packed into a compressed data block group with integral number of the compressed data blocks, the last compressed data block in the group may include padding if there is no enough data to fill one compressed data block. The input uncompressed data block size is set by CompUDblkSize field in request message, and the output compressed data block size is set by CompDblkSize field in request message as well. The input data stream to compression engine consists multiple uncompressed data blocks, and similarly the output data stream from the compression engine consists multiple compressed blocks. The input data stream to the compression engine may include partial block data at beginning (CompDataOffset > 0) or at end ( < CompUDBlkSize). Those partial block data shall bypass compression operation and moves directly from input data stream to output data stream, see Figure 2.

The compressed data length and total compressed data block numbers per input uncompressed data block are captured in 4 byte compression meta data which shall be included in completion message and optionally inserted at the beginning of the compressed data before packing. CRC (Adler32 / GZIP-CRC32) over the compressed data is optionally inserted at the back of the compressed data stream before packing. Bit CompMetaDataIns and bit CompCRCIns are used to enable or disable (0 for no insertion, 1 for insertion) compression meta data and CRC insertion respectively.

In case of incompressible data block, the data after compression is larger or equal to uncompressed data, either original data or the compressed data (inflated in fact in this case) will be used for packing depending on the control bit CompInCompOut in the request message. Compression meta data includes compressed data block type (CDBT) to indicate which data type is packed.
There are several data structures defined for compression operations, see Figure 3.
Data Structure 0 is the raw uncompressed data block, the size of data block is set by CompUDBlkSize field in the request message.
Data Structure 1 is the compressed data from compression core appended 32-bit CRC in the end.

Data Structure 2 is the compressed data block group after packing the compressed data of data structure 1. The data structure 2 includes integer number of compressed data block. The size of the compressed data block is set by CompDBlkSize. The first data block includes compression meta data appended in beginning. The last data block may include padding zeros the compressed data size plus compression meta data is not aligned to compressed block size.
Data Structure 3 is the same as the compressed data block group except uncompressed data, instead of compressed data, used for packing.
Compression meta data is 32-bit wide, includes compressed block number, compressed data length, and data type (uncomrpessed or compressed) as defined in Table 1

li.p: Each of 8 slices can support up to 1.25GB/S throughput (uncompressed data), total compression engine throughput is up to 10GB/S. Each slice performs compression operation for each uncompressed data block atomically, hence an uncompressed data block can not intervening between two slices. To saturate 10GB/S, at least 8 input uncompressed data blocks shall be compressed in parallel at any given time. Those uncompressed data blocks compressed in parallel may come from the same request or multiple requests. The order of output compressed data blocks from different slices shall be maintained as if there is only one compression slice performs compression operations: For the same request, the output compressed data blocks in the output data stream shall be in order as input uncompressed data blocks in input data stream; The compressed data streams from different requests shall not interleaving in between, and shall be in order of the same as corresponding request messages.

The 4 byte compression meta data for each input uncompressed data block is always captured in the completion message. If there is no hash digest in completion message, then the completion message supports up to 73 compression meta data field and with format as shown in Figure 4. When there is/are hash digest(s) in completion message, completion message supports up to 9 compression meta data field and with format as shown in Figure 4 and Figure 5. topic.title: Encryption Engine

li.p:
Encryption engine in the ingress data processing unit performs the basic function of encrypting the input data and sends the encrypted data to the output port of the ingress data processing subsystem. The encryption function is in compliant to FIPS 197 Advanced Encryption Standard with key size of 256-bit.
Two AES block cipher modes are supported in the encryption engine and they are selected by EncrCipherMode in an ingress inbound message request.
AES XTS mode - This mode is in compliant to NIST SP 800-38E (IEEE Std.1619-2007). When the input block size is not aligned to 16-byte AES block cipher, cipher text stealing (CTS) is used. AES XTS mode uses two AES 256-bit keys, one to tweak the value and other for data encryption.
AES ECB mode - This mode is compliant to NIST SP 800-38A. The encryption engine does not support ECB cipher text stealing. If the input block or data length is not 16-byte block cipher aligned, it will be reported as a message error.
The encryption engine supports block based encryption only and supports fixed block size, selected by EncrBlkMode in the inbound message request.
For fixed block size mode, the encryption data block size is defined by input block size EncrBlkSize in the inbound message request. The block size applies to the whole data stream.
The encryption engine supports skip feature, which skips the programmed number of bytes (4,8,or 16 bytes by EncrSkipNum in the current request message) at the beginning of an encryption data block or at the end of encryption data block, as shown in the following figure: Encryption Skip
The 128-bit initial tweak value for XTS cipher mode is carried in EncrTweakInit field. It is using just the first encryption data block. The tweak value or the initial value is incremented by 1 per block for other encrypted data block.
The data encryption key (DEK) is fetched from a key table inside an encryption unit external to the ingress data processing subsystem. The DEK used for the current request is addressed by a key index EncrDEKIndex in the request message. The DEK key blob includes two 256-bit AES keys; DEK1 and DEK2. For XTS cipher mode, both DEK1 and DEK2 are used: DEK1 is used for data cipher and DEK2 is used for tweak cipher. For ECB cipher mode, only DEK1 is used and DEK2 is ignored, as shown in the following figure: DEK Blob
The DEK integrity check may be enabled by bit EncrDEKTagCheck in the request message. If enabled, the key tag from the DEK blob is checked with the key tag EncrDEKTagL/H in the request message. If there is a mismatch, it will be reported in the completion message.

table.title: IDP_CTL - Ingress DPS Control

field-desc.p: This field controls the operational state of the Ingress DPS. Modifying the value of this field causes the queue to transition to the specified operational state. A transition does not complete until the new operational state is reflected in the State (STATE) field in the corresponding Ingress DPS Status (IDP_STS) register.
A direct transition from the enabled to disabled state is not supported.
Firmware must comprehend the possibility of an autonomous state transition to disabled due to an error.

description.p: This bit configures whether compression 4-byte statistic meta data per uncompressed block is generated and inserted to compressed data for each uncompressed data block or entire uncompressed data stream.

If it is set to 0, no compression meta is attached. If it is set to 1, the 4-byte compression meta data is generated and inserted at the beginning of the first compressed data block for each uncompressed data block in block based compression mode.
The 4-byte compression meta data for block based compression includes 2-byte compressed data block counter with packing information and 2-byte compressed data length.
This bit configures whether compression 4-byte CRC per uncompressed block is generated and inserted to compressed data for each uncompressed data block or entire uncompressed data stream.

If it is set to 0, no CRC is attached. If it is set to 1, the 4-byte CRC (Adler32 checksum) is generated and inserted at the end of the compressed data for each uncompressed data block in block based compression mode.

This bit configures whether the compressed data integrity is checked. If it is set to '0', no data integrity check for compressed data. If it is set to '1', the data integrity check is performed by decompressing the compressed data with embedded decompress logic inside the ingress DPU, and checking the Adler32 checksum.
This bit is ignored and no data integrity check will be performed for the compressed data if Adler32 checksum is not enabled (CompCRCIns=0)
This bit configures whether the compression unit will output original data before compression or compressed data after compression if the data block is incompressible.
If it is set to 0, the compression unit will output the compressed data (which means its size is larger than uncompressed data). If it is set to 1, the compression unit will output the original data.
